{
  "text": "Similarly, F4 I, which had the highest drug permeability in the ex vivo experiments, possessed a 164.15% relative bioavailability compared to Zaditen\u00ae Novartis solution. The sublingual mucosa had a high ability to give more uniform and higher rates of transmission, and rabbit anesthesia helped to hold the tablet in its place without swallowing it [CITATION_1] . That allowed a maximum amount of drug to be available for absorption through the sublingual mucosa.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "29259846"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "29259846": {
      "title": "Penetration of water through human and rabbit oral mucosa in vitro",
      "abstract": "Abstract Using tritiated water and a modified diffusion chamber, the rate of transmission of water across buccal and sublingual mucous membrane was measured. The rate of transmission was 10 to 100 times faster than that reported for the skin. Sublingual mucosa gave more uniform and higher rates of transmission than buccal mucosa. The results were of the same order as those reported for human oral mucosa using an in vivo technique by Kaaber (1971a, 1971b and 1971c). Saliva applied to the membranes in some cases caused a slight and transitory decrease in the rate of transmission of water when compared with control rates."
    }
  }
}